\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 9. A. ruscinonensis} Girard,{\i  Ann. Sci. Nat.} ser. 3,{\b  2:} 323 (1844) ({\i A. majellensis} auct. gall. et hisp., non Boiss.). Dwarf shrub, with a usually long-branched, rather stout stock, sometimes a herb with a shortly branched stock. Leaves 40-90(-170) × 2-4(-6) mm, numerous, linear or linear-spathulate, flat or some canaliculate or more or less convolute, subobtuse, muticous, with narrow scarious margins, becoming coriaceous. Scapes (7-)10-20(-40) cm, arcuate or flexuous. Sheath 10-24(-30) mm. Capitula 15-20 mm wide; outer involucral bracts as long as or longer than the inner, usually acuminate-cuspidate, with narrow scarious margins. Spikelets more or less stipitate; bract shorter than calyx. Calyx 6-8 mm; tube hirsute on ribs; awns 1-1·5 mm. Corolla pinkish or white. 2n = 18.{\i  Maritime cliffs and mountains near the sea, up to 1300 m; calcifuge. • S. France, N.E. Spain}.Ga Hs.
